# L2-DEC-015 borderline-detection fixture.
#
# Five records (80 bytes) hand-crafted to demonstrate the value of the
# multi-record probe: single-record probe (--detect-records 1) picks
# the wrong timestamp format (Standard); the default 8-record probe
# picks the right format (IRIG) decisively.
#
# Record 1 is shaped to favor Standard:
#   * Type Word 0x0802 (BC_TO_RT, wc=8) — same TypeWord across all 5
#     records (homogeneity defense doesn't fire because record 1's
#     bytes [8..16) differ from records 2-5's, satisfying L2-SYN-018).
#   * Standard Cmd at offset+6 (raw 0x7963): RT=15, T/R=Receive
#     (matches BC_TO_RT, +2 STD T/R), data_word_count=3 (matches
#     wc-5=3, +2 STD WC). Standard score: +4.
#   * IRIG Cmd at offset+8 (raw 0x0400): T/R bit set so direction=
#     Transmit (does NOT match BC_TO_RT, no +2), dwc=0 (doesn't
#     match wc-6=2, no +2). IRIG range: ts_upper=0x001F gives
#     hour=31 (>23), fails (no +1). IRIG score: 0.
#   * Net per-record: IRIG=0, STD=4. Standard wins by 4.
#
# Records 2-5 are valid IRIG-format records:
#   * Same Type Word 0x0802.
#   * IRIG TS: day=192, hour=15, min=54, sec=50 (all valid).
#   * IRIG Cmd at offset+8 (raw 0x7962): RT=15, T/R=Receive
#     (matches BC_TO_RT, +2 IRIG T/R), dwc=2 (matches wc-6=2,
#     +2 IRIG WC). IRIG range valid (+1). IRIG score: 5.
#   * Standard Cmd at offset+6 (the IRIG ts_lower, raw 0x0000):
#     direction=Receive (matches BC_TO_RT, +2 STD T/R), dwc=0
#     (doesn't match wc-5=3, no +2). Standard score: 2.
#   * Data[0] (bytes 10-11) varies per record (0x0001, 0x0002,
#     0x0003, 0x0004) so records 2-4 aren't byte-identical for
#     L2-SYN-018 — though that defense already returns false on the
#     record-1-vs-record-2 comparison.
#
# Aggregate at N=1: IRIG=0, STD=4. Standard Marginal.
# Aggregate at N=5+: IRIG=0+5*4=20, STD=4+2*4=12. IRIG Decisive
# (max_score >= DECISIVE_FLOOR=8 AND margin >= DECISIVE_MARGIN=6).
#
# Default --detect-records 8 walks all 5 available records (probe
# stops at EOF), yielding IRIG Decisive. The two conformance cases
# (default + --detect-records 1) demonstrate the cross-impl
# behavioral difference.
0208 1F00 FFFF 6379 0004 0000 0000 0000
0208 0F18 20DB 0000 6279 0100 0000 0000
0208 0F18 20DB 0000 6279 0200 0000 0000
0208 0F18 20DB 0000 6279 0300 0000 0000
0208 0F18 20DB 0000 6279 0400 0000 0000
